# ROCm/HIP cmake root-level inventory

upstream_repo: ROCm/hip
upstream_path: cmake/
source_view: GitHub mobile file browser screenshots supplied by project owner
created_for: Netiv ROCN research library
scope: cmake/ first-level folders and files only, plus observed cmake/FindHIP first-level files
status: manual staged inventory

FORMAT:
path | kind | apparent purpose

================================================================================
CMAKE FIRST-LEVEL ENTRIES
================================================================================
cmake/FindHIP/ | folder | CMake helper folder for finding/configuring HIP in external CMake projects.
cmake/FindHIP.cmake | CMake module | Main CMake module for locating HIP and exposing HIP build configuration to CMake consumers.

================================================================================
CMAKE/FINDHIP FIRST-LEVEL FILES
================================================================================
cmake/FindHIP/run_hipcc.cmake | CMake helper | Helper script for running HIP compiler-driver behavior through CMake.
cmake/FindHIP/run_make2cmake.cmake | CMake helper | Helper script for translating or bridging make-style HIP build behavior into CMake flow.

================================================================================
ROCN NOTES
================================================================================
This folder matters later, not first.

For ROCN, cmake/ should be studied after docs/ and include/hip/ because it is mostly build-system integration rather than the core API surface.

Likely ROCN mapping:

1. cmake/FindHIP.cmake
   Map to future Netiv build backend discovery behavior.

2. cmake/FindHIP/run_hipcc.cmake
   Study how HIP compiler-driver calls are staged from a build system.

3. cmake/FindHIP/run_make2cmake.cmake
   Study how HIP build assumptions are translated into CMake-compatible form.

Do not copy this build system yet. Use it as a model for a future ROCN build adapter only after ROCN has a stable host/kernel/memory design.
